# Compose modifier / Modifier rules (mandatory)

Kotlin is case-sensitive. Never mix these three:

| Role | Correct spelling |
|------|------------------|
| import type | `import androidx.compose.ui.Modifier` (**capital M**) |
| parameter / local var | `modifier` (**lowercase m**) |
| type / companion factory | `Modifier` (**capital M**) |

## 1. import MUST be capital-M Modifier (most common mistake)

```kotlin
// BAD — package does not exist; compile fails
import androidx.compose.ui.modifier

// GOOD — capital M
import androidx.compose.ui.Modifier
```

When creating any new Compose file, verify this import first. Do not carry the lowercase parameter name `modifier` into the import path.

## 2. Named argument must be lowercase modifier

```kotlin
// BAD — uppercase named arg breaks Box content overload match
Box(Modifier = Modifier.fillMaxWidth()) { ... }

// GOOD — lowercase arg name, uppercase type/factory
Box(modifier = Modifier.fillMaxWidth()) { ... }
```

## 3. Prefer explicit `modifier = Modifier.…`

```kotlin
// BAD
Column(modifier.weight(1f)) { ... }

// GOOD
Column(modifier = Modifier.weight(1f)) { ... }

// GOOD — chain lowercase only when the param exists
@Composable
fun Foo(modifier: Modifier = Modifier) {
    Column(modifier = modifier.fillMaxWidth()) { ... }
}
```

## Checklist after editing Compose UI

1. Import is exactly: `import androidx.compose.ui.Modifier` (capital M)
2. Named args use lowercase: `modifier =`
3. New chains use capital: `Modifier.…`
4. Lowercase `modifier.xxx` only if the function declares `modifier: Modifier`
